    <stitle>VT-365 Diesel Engine Diagnostics (2002) - PERFORMANCE DIAGNOSTICS - Test Procedures - EGR position</stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc graphiccount="4">
        <title>EGR position</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <figure id="f2400638" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figD31/D3145.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            </figure>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Purpose</emph>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>To check the EGR position when commanded close or open</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Is the EGR valve sticking or stuck?</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para></para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Tools</emph>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Electronic Service Tool (EST) with Master Diagnostics software</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>International&#174; EZ-Tech Interface Cable</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>EGR breakout harness</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>DMM</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid serious personal injury, possible death, or damage to the engine or vehicle, read all
                        safety instructions in the foreword of this manual. Follow all warnings, cautions, and notes.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Monitoring EGR position using EST</title>
            <para></para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">See Appendix A in this manual for specifications, and record on Performance Diagnostics
                    form.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove engine harness connector from EGR valve.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f2400639" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figD31/D31155.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>EGR breakout harness installed</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To prevent serious personal injury, possible death, or damage to the engine or vehicle -
                        comply with the following:
                    </para>
                    <para>When routing DMM leads, do not crimp the leads, run the leads too close to moving parts, or
                        let the leads touch hot engine surfaces.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Connect EGR breakout harness to engine harness and EGR valve.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use DMM to measure EGR position voltage.</para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>Connect POS to green (signal circuit) and NEG to black (signal ground).</para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f2400640" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figD31/D31197.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>KOER Air Management.ssn</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Open KOER Air Management.ssn to monitor EGR position.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Turn ignition key ON. (Do not start the engine.)</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Record the value for the EGR (% closed) and voltage value (DMM) on diagnostics form.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f2400641" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figD31/D31143.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="yes"/>
                <caption>Output State Test Low</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Select Diagnostics from menu bar.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Select Key On Engine Off Tests from drop down menu.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">From the Key On Engine Off Diagnostics menu, select Output State Low Test, then Run to
                    energize coil and open EGR valve.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Monitor EGRP % (open) and voltage value (DMM) and record on diagnostics form.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Click Cancel Test.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Subtract EGRP % (open) from EGRP % (closed) to get travel percent and record on
                    diagnostics form.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Subtract (open) voltage from (closed) voltage and record diagnostics form.</para>
                <para>If both travel percent and voltage travel are below spec., replace EGR valve and retest.</para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Initial ECM calibrations for DTC 365 and DTC 366 could become active during the test. Ignore
                        and clear DTC 365 and DTC 366 when done.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Possible Causes</emph>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Problem in EGR control circuit</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Defective EGR valve</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Defective ECM</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
